04157nam a22004575i 9780674250673DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742506737 a10.4159/97806742506732doi  a(DE-B1597)567547  a(OCoLC)1195824124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBUS0000002bisacsh1 aChancel, Lucas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnsustainable Inequalities /cLucas Chancel. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE The Sources of Unsustainable Development -- t1 Economic Inequality as a Component of Unsustainability -- t2 Trends and Drivers of Economic Inequality -- tPART TWO The Vicious Circle of Environmental and Social Inequalities -- t3 Unequal Access to Environmental Resources -- t4 Unequal Exposure to Environmental Risks -- t5 Unequal Responsibility for Pollution -- tPART THREE Political, Social, and Economic Policy Implications -- t6 Reducing Inequalities in a Finite World -- t7 Local Organization vs. International Coordination -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA hardheaded book that confronts and outlines possible solutions to a seemingly intractable problem: that helping the poor often hurts the environment, and vice versa.Can we fight poverty and inequality while protecting the environment? The challenges are obvious. To rise out of poverty is to consume more resources, almost by definition. And many measures to combat pollution lead to job losses and higher prices that mainly hurt the poor. In Unsustainable Inequalities, economist Lucas Chancel confronts these difficulties head-on, arguing that the goals of social justice and a greener world can be compatible, but that progress requires substantial changes in public policy.Chancel begins by reviewing the problems. Human actions have put the natural world under unprecedented pressure. The poor are least to blame but suffer the most—forced to live with pollutants that the polluters themselves pay to avoid. But Chancel shows that policy pioneers worldwide are charting a way forward. Building on their success, governments and other large-scale organizations must start by doing much more simply to measure and map environmental inequalities. We need to break down the walls between traditional social policy and environmental protection—making sure, for example, that the poor benefit most from carbon taxes. And we need much better coordination between the center, where policies are set, and local authorities on the front lines of deprivation and contamination.A rare work that combines the quantitative skills of an economist with the argumentative rigor of a philosopher, Unsustainable Inequalities shows that there is still hope for solving even seemingly intractable social problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425067340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674250673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674250673.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles